Endangered species should not be used.
Two types of behaviour involving movement
could be investigated:
Taxis is movement towards or away from a
directional stimulus. An example is movement
of a woodlouse or slater away from light.
Kinesis also involves movement as a response,
but the direction of movement is not
inuenced by the stimulus. Instead, the speed
of movement or the number of times the
animal turns is varied. An example is slower
movement, with more frequent turning, when
woodlice are transferred from drier to more
damp conditions.
Stages in designing an investigation:
Place the animals in conditions that are similar
to the natural habitat.
Observe the behaviour and see what stimuli
affect movement.
Choose one stimulus that appears to cause a
taxis or kinesis.
Devise an experiment to test responses to the
stimulus.
Ensure that other factors do not have an effect
on the movement.
Decide how to measure the movement of the
invertebrates.
Reexes
Autonomic and involuntary responses are referred
to as reexes.
A stimulus is a change in the environment, either internal or external,
that is detected by a receptor and elicits a response. A response is a
change in an organism, often carried out by a muscle or a gland. Some
responses happen without conscious thought and are therefore called
involuntary responses. Many of these are controlled by the autonomic
nervous system. These autonomic and involuntary responses are known
as reexes.
A reex is a rapid unconscious response to a stimulus. The pupil
reex is an example: in response to the stimulus of bright light,
the radial muscles in the iris of the eye contract, constricting the
pupil. This involuntary response is carried out by the autonomic
nervoussystem.
Reex arcs
Reex arcs comprise the neurons that mediate reexes.
All reexes start with a receptor that perceives the stimulus and ends
with an effector, usually a muscle or gland, which carries out the
response. Linking the receptor to the effector is a sequence of neurons,
with synapses between them. The sequence of neurons is known as a
reex arc. In the simplest reex arcs there are two neurons: a sensory
neuron to carry impulses from the receptor to a synapse with a motor
neuron in the spinal cord and a motor neuron to carry impulses on to
the effector. Most reex arcs contain more than two neurons, as there
are one or more relay neurons connecting the sensory neuron to the
motor neuron.
